The paper presents a novel clustering algorithm that adapts its parameters during execution to unravel physical clusters in the data. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The use of possibilistic clustering also suggests that it may belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) or social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on clustering and convergence behavior suggests that it may also belong to the data mining (cs.DM) sub-category.
